Enterprise High School
May 12 at 12:46 PM ·

Graduation Plans...revised! More information will be out by the end of this week!

- We are still limiting graduates to only six guests. Guest are encouraged to wear masks and sit six feet apart and skip rows. Graduates should wear masks until time to walk on the field.
-Guest will only be allowed to sit on the home side.
-Guest and students are to park in the Red Lot and enter the stadium from there.
- We hope to have six tickets for students to pickup next week for their guest.
-The times for graduation are as follows 8am, 11am, 2pm, and 5 pm. We will have the lists of names and times posted by the end of this week.
-Seniors are not required to participate in order to recieve their diploma. Diplomas will be availble to pick up Friday from 9-11am for anyone that does not attend the ceremony.
-We will have a window from 9am to 11am on the 20th in the PAC for any graduate and family that does not feel comfortable participating in the ceremony on the 21st.

post_text:
Due to the negative economic impact COVID-19 has had on many of our families, the tuition deadline for currently enrolled out of district students who plan to attend Enterprise schools during the 2020-2021 school year has been pushed back to October 30, 2020. Families are reminded that partial payments can be made online at any time or in person once schools open for business.

New out of district students wishing to attend Enterprise City Schools during the 2020-2021 school year must complete an out of district enrollment form and pay the tuition in full before being enrolled.

Tuition is $300 for each of the first two students and $150 for each additional student.

Gregory S. Faught,
Superintendent Enterprise City Schools

2020 - 2021 Kindergarten Registration

Packets have been placed outside of EEEC's frontdoors for you to pickup if you would like.

Please complete the packets and attach copies of the Birth Certificate, current Alabama Immunization Record, Social Security, and two proofs of address (ex. Lease, light or cable and do one of the following.

Thank you so much.

shared_text:
Auburn University Honors College
April 29 at 4:30 PM ·

Paxton Peacock will be graduating as a University Honors Scholar majoring in Animal Sciences this spring. He was accepted into several medical schools and has chosen to attend UAB Medical School in the fall with a combined MD/MBA dual degree. While at Auburn, Paxton was involved in undergraduate research, was a COSAM UR Ambassador, and participated in a Healthcare Policy internship in Washington, D.C. last summer. He recently received the 2020 Algernon Sydney Sullivan Award that is given annually to individuals who embody high qualities and nobility of character at Auburn University. Congratulations Paxton, thank you for being part of the Honors College and #WarEagle

post_text:
As of April 9, 2020, Enterprise City Schools Child Nutrition Program will suspend the feeding program until further notice. With COVID-19 cases increasing in Alabama and our community, it is in the best interest of the health and safety of our employees, our volunteers and the community we serve that we discontinue this service. We will give out 3 breakfasts and 3 lunches on Wednesday, April 8th, deliveries will start at 11:00 am at the 9 locations across Enterprise. Continue to check our website and Facebook page for announcements of reopening. Thank you to all our CNP staff and volunteers that helped feed our students during this unprecedented closure; we are praying for health and safety over our students, staff and communities.

God Bless you all,
Julie Harmon
Enterprise City Schools

post_text: Over the last week, Enterprise City Schools Central Office staff has been in regular contact to develop tentative plans in the event traditional school would be cancelled this year. After the briefing with Dr. Mackey this morning, our staff is working on the logistical means and methods to deliver the most important content standards to our students as soon as possible after spring break. This process also includes identifying key resources, accessibility for students, reasonable assessment procedures, and other potential pathways to success. While this situation is not ideal for many of us, we ask for your patience as we work through this uncertain time. Our team will do everything within its power to provide meaningful online and/or blended learning opportunities for the remainder of the school year. Please stay safe and check our website periodically for updates.

Kindergarten Classes for Zoned Elementary Schools

Enterprise City Schools will continue to have kindergarten classes located at each of the elementary schools for the 2020-2021 school year. If you are interested in having your kindergarten student attend the school for which they are zoned, please complete the request for enrollment located on the Enterprise City Schools website.

In addition to this form, please make sure that you have filled out a Kindergarten registration packet at Enterprise Early Education Center (EEEC).

Please complete this information by Friday, April 17th.

Enterprise Chamber of Commerce added 3 new photos to the album: Innovative Teaching Grant Presentation — with Enterprise High School and Rucker Boulevard Elementary School.
February 26 at 12:05 PM ·

On February 26th and 27th, the Workforce and Education Partnership Team at the Enterprise Chamber of Commerce awarded three grants. One of the grants went to the Enterprise High School, Wildcat Industries, they were awarded with a $500 check for T-Shirt Butlers that will assist with workplace skills. Another grant of $900 was presented to the Enterprise High School, Cat Scholars for FitDesks that will allow Cat Scholars to be able to pedal on a stationary bike while reading and responding to reading instruction. Last but not least, Rucker Boulevard Elementary School was awarded $600 for cardio drumming that will engage students through music and physical education.

Preparación de Impuestos GRATUITA:

Tú lo ganaste. Tú lo reclamas

Si ganaste $68,000 o menos en el año 2019, calificas para la preparación de impuestos gratuita a partir del 20 de enero en el Centro de Servicios a la Familia del Condado de Coffee.

Qué llevar a la cita: identificación con foto (contribuyente y cónyuge), W2, tarjetas de Seguro Social para contribuyente, cónyuge y dependientes, formularios 1098 y 1099, 1098T (beneficios educativos), formulario 1095 (seguro médico), información de la cuenta bancaria, número de identificación del proveedor de cuidado infantil y declaración de impuestos del año pasado.

208 West Brunson Street, Enterprise. Lunes a viernes 9:00-3:00 y lunes por la noche desde las 5:30-8:00. Para más información llame a 393-8538.

No te dejes caer en la trampa de los préstamos de reembolsos anticipados. Nuestros servicios son GRATUITOS y NO HAY COSTOS OCULTOS.

Enterprise High School
December 12, 2019 at 7:50 PM ·

****Tomorrow, Joshua Kaleb Watson will return home to Enterprise. The plane bringing Josh home is set to land in Dothan around 10 am. In coordination will EPD, EHS will walk our students down to the bypass and line both sides and honor Josh and his family on his way to Searcy's Funeral home.

Students, please dress accordingly tomorrow. It will be cool much like today and there is a chance of rain. We will monitor the weather very closely and make a determination whether or not to walk down just before time to do so. If you have American flags, please feel free to bring them to school tomorrow.

******There is a change in the route tomorrow. The procession will proceed straight through down town. We will walk to Main Street instead.

post_text:
George Washington Carver Living Exhibit

It was such an honor to witness students reflect, recall and share the life of Dr. George Washington Carver. Young and old from all walks of life were able to gain nuggets and truths in regards to Dr. Carver.

Dr. Carver was a man of many gifts and talents. He was a scientist, an artist, a leader, a humanitarian, a poet, a Bible scholar, an educator, a man of great faith. He was a man for all people.
￼
Thanks for listening, sharing memories, and supporting Dr. George Washington Carver’s Living Exhibit!

Our students were amazing!

“It is not the style of clothes one wears, neither the kind of automobile one drives, nor the amount of money one has in the bank, that counts. These mean nothing. It is simply service that measures success.”
George Washington Carver

Our principal, Mr. Steed, read the book Billy Boll Weevil to all of our students through a video.
